abstract.para: This study evaluated habitat use of each species in relation to thermal conditions in the reservoir
complex, and described how annual reservoir elevation patterns influenced the spatial distribution of
fish. Specifically, the study a) documented seasonal habitat use by fish in four macrohabitat types of the
CML reservoir complex - Masonry Pool (MP), the main basin, delta, and the reservoir/river transition
zone; b) documented the seasonal and diel depth of bull trout and rainbow trout in the main basin of
CML, and c) described thermal conditions for bull trout and rainbow trout.
The adult fish tagging study was part of a larger effort to better understand distribution of adult bull trout,
rainbow trout and pygmy whitefish in the reservoir complex. Results corroborated bioenergetics
simulations, indicating that bull trout in CML occupy thermally suitable habitats during stratification such
that they do not experience prolonged stress or weight loss. Adult bull trout occurred throughout CML
but exhibited seasonal changes in depth and lateral distribution. Masonry Pool, on the west side of the
complex, was the least utilized habitat, and most tagged fish remained distributed at the eastern end of
CML where the Cedar and Rex rivers flow into CML. Bull trout use of the Cedar and Rex deltas was high
from winter through spring, and in summer bull trout moved to deeper and presumably cooler habitats
in the main CML basin. Concurrent detections of pygmy whitefish and bull trout in deltas during winter
and spring, along with increased proportion of pygmy whitefish in bull trout diets during these seasons,
suggested that delta habitats may be important foraging habitat for bull trout in spring.

description.para: Acoustic telemetry equipment (Vemco, Inc., Shad Bay, Nova Scotia, Canada) was used to continuously monitor the location of adult bull trout, rainbow trout, and pygmy whitefish in the reservoir complex, and provided depth and temperature at fish locations for some tagged fish. These data confirmed fish were within a general detection area of a receiver, and were useful in describing macrohabitat scale distribution patterns.

Hydrophone receivers (VR2 and VR2W receivers) mounted to buoys (n = 22) were positioned in the reservoir complex (Figure 7-2). The receiver array provided only partial coverage in MP, the main basin, deltas, and the reservoir/river transition zone. Additional receivers were installed upstream of the reservoir/river transition zone in the Cedar (n = 7) and Rex (n = 6) rivers, and in Rack Creek (n = 1) to document movements within stream habitats. The detection range of acoustic tags was about 300 m at full pool elevation. Data were downloaded quarterly at which time receivers were replaced with a new unit.

Data from receivers were combined on two levels to describe an individual's horizontal position in the reservoir complex; a) habitat zones, and b) macrohabitat types. Habitat zones were composed of a grouping of receivers within a localized area. This provided a useful partitioning of data to support project planning (e.g., Morse Lake Pump Plant project), and enabled finer-scale evaluation of habitat use within discrete portions of the reservoir. Summary of data by macrohabitat types provided a coarser description of habitat use, and included a) MP, b) main basin, c) delta, and d) river/reservoir transition habitat.

project.abstract: Bull trout lake telemetry [N541808] The City may tag and acoustically track adult bull trout in the Chester Morse Lake to learn if they might be spawning at selected locations in the reservoir. The cost of this study may be up to $70,000 and may be initiated within HCP years 39.
